{"text": "condition q 0\u27e9= 0 (i.e., the zero energy state at mass domain wall is unoccupied), then\n\nthe occupied state 1\u27e9can be defined as 1\u27e9= q\u2020 0\u27e9, which is degenerate (E = 0) with 0\u27e9.\n\nThe conventional fermion occupation number operator n = q\u2020q can be expressed in terms\n\nof the Majorana operators \u03b3+, \u03b3\u2212as, n = q\u2020q = 1\n\n2(1 + i\u03b3+\u03b3\u2212). Conversely, the operator\n\ni\u03b3+\u03b3\u2212= 2q\u2020q \u22121, which takes the value 1 in the state 1\u27e9and \u22121 in the state 0\u27e9, is called\n\nthe fermion parity operator. It is now clear that the conventional fermionic mode described\n\nby q\u2020, q allows us to define a pair of Majorana zero modes, but the two MZMs \u03b3+, \u03b3\u2212do\n\nnot occur separately in space, describe the same localized wave function \u03c60(x) in Eq. 22,\n\nand should really be viewed as a basis transformation from the creation and annihilation\n\noperators q\u2020, q to the Majorana operators \u03b3+, \u03b3\u2212.\n\nThe goal of the ongoing research on\n\nMajorana fermions in condensed matter systems is to create experimental conditions so\n\nthat individual Majorana zero modes (e.g., \u03b3+ or \u03b3\u2212) can occur spatially well-separated\n\nfrom each other. It is only in this limit they individually acquire topological protection.\n\nB.\n\n2D Spinless (px + ipy) superconductor\n\nThe 2D spinless (px + ipy) superconductor (superfluid) is the canonical system that sup-\n\nports zero energy MZMs localized at the defects of the order parameter, such as vortices and\n\nsample edges19. In 2D the mean field Hamiltonian describing the quasiparticle excitations\n\nfor such a system is given by,\n\nHp\n\n2D =\n\nX\n\np\n\n\u03bepc\u2020\n\npcp + \u22060\n\nX\n\np\n\nh\n\n(px + ipy)c\u2020\n\npc\u2020\n\n\u2212p + h.c.\n\ni\n\n,\n\n(26)\n\nwhere \u03bep = \u03b5p \u2212\u03bc with \u03b5p \u2192\n\np2\n\n2m\u2217for small p, m\u2217is the effective mass, and \u0